---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import OrnamentRule from "../components/ui/OrnamentRule.astro";
import victoria from "../assets/victoria.avif?url";
---

<Layout title="About | The language of flowers">
  <main class="min-h-screen romance-page-bg">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-4 py-10 md:py-14">
      <header class="text-center mb-12 max-w-2xl mx-auto">
        <p class="font-display italic text-brand-mauve/90 text-lg mb-2">A little history</p>
        <h1
          class="font-display text-4xl md:text-5xl font-semibold text-brand-wine mb-4 leading-tight"
        >
          The language of flowers
        </h1>
        <OrnamentRule class="mb-6" />
        <p class="text-brand-forest/75 text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed font-light">
          How a tussie mussie whispered devotion, consolation, or hope—without ever
          opening the lips.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="max-w-3xl romance-card rounded-2xl p-8 md:p-10 mx-auto">
        <div class="prose-flow prose prose-lg max-w-none text-brand-forest/85">
          <p class="p-4">
            Floriography, or the language of flowers, is a means of
            cryptological communication through the use or arrangement of
            flowers. Dating back to the Victorian era, this practice allowed
            people to express feelings which otherwise could not be spoken.
          </p>

          <div class="my-8 flex justify-center">
            <img
              src={victoria}
              alt="Queen Victoria with a Tussie Mussie"
              class="rounded-lg shadow-md"
              height="600"
              width="600"
            />
          </div>
          <p class="text-sm text-brand-forest/55 p-2 text-center italic">
            Queen Victoria popularized tussie mussies. Image from the Royal
            Collection Trust
          </p>

          <h2 class="font-display text-2xl text-brand-wine mt-10 mb-4">Cultural significance</h2>
          <p class="p-4">
            The language of flowers varies across different cultures and time
            periods. In Victorian England, elaborate flower dictionaries were
            published, allowing people to create bouquets that conveyed specific
            messages.
          </p>

          <h2 class="font-display text-2xl text-brand-wine mt-10 mb-4">Sources & data</h2>
          <p class="p-4">
            This data was taken from the             <a
              class="text-brand-mauve underline decoration-brand-blossom/55 underline-offset-2 hover:text-brand-wine"
              href="https://www.almanac.com/flower-meanings-language-flowers#flower-meanings"
            >
              Farmer's Almanac</a
            >, and generally corresponds to the English-speaking Victorian
            understanding of 'floriography', or the secret meanings of flowers.
            Messages could be transmitted by sending just the right combination
            of flowers in a bouquet or 'tussie mussie'. Note, there are many of
            these types of lists; the canonical one was the French book, "Le
            Langage des Fleurs" by "Madame Charlotte de la Tour", written in
            1809. This book was translated and reinnterpreted several times in
            the Victorian era, triggering a fashion for these meaningful
            bouquets.             <a
              class="text-brand-mauve underline decoration-brand-blossom/55 underline-offset-2 hover:text-brand-wine"
              href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Language_of_flowers">Source</a
            >
          </p>

          <h2 class="font-display text-2xl text-brand-wine mt-10 mb-4">Weaving meaning</h2>
          <p class="p-4">
            When creating a bouquet using the language of flowers, consider not
            only the meaning of each individual flower but also how they
            complement each other. A thoughtfully composed arrangement can tell
            a story or express complex emotions. The color of a given flower,
            like a rose, carnation, or tulip, can change its meaning.
          </p>

          <h2 class="font-display text-2xl text-brand-wine mt-10 mb-4">Today</h2>
          <p class="p-4">
            Today, while we may not rely on flowers to communicate secret
            messages, understanding the traditional meanings can add depth and
            thoughtfulness to gift-giving and special occasions. Our bouquet
            creator helps you craft arrangements with intention and meaning and
            download an image or send an e-card (when configured) to share. It's a great gift for a birthday or Mother's
            Day, or really any occasion. You could also use this generator to
            create a meaningful bouquet using real flowers.
          </p>

          <div
            class="mt-10 p-6 bg-gradient-to-br from-brand-sky/25 to-brand-blush/35 rounded-2xl border border-brand-blush/50"
          >
            <p class="font-display italic text-center text-brand-wine text-lg leading-relaxed">
              “The Earth laughs in flowers.” — Ralph Waldo Emerson
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-10 text-center">
          <a
            href="/"
            class="inline-block px-8 py-3.5 rounded-xl bg-gradient-to-br from-brand-wine to-brand-mauve text-white hover:shadow-lg transition-all shadow-lg shadow-brand-wine/22 border border-brand-wine/30 font-medium"
          >
            Return to the garden
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>
